The CoG in partnership with the Ministry of Transport has secured Sh3 billion financing for infrastructure development across 45 counties.The funds, under the Kenya Urban Support Programme, will be financed by the World Bank. Sh2.7 billion will go directly to 45 counties, while Sh300 million will be deposited with the national government. &ldquo;The objective of the programME is to establish and strengthen urban institutions to deliver improved infrastructure and services in participating counties. The programme is expected to provide direct support to all counties other than Nairobi and Mombasa, and to 59 potentially eligible urban areas within the 45 counties,&rdquo; the statement reads. The statement, signed by the CoG director of communications Andrew Teiye, said the urban planning department has been working with the Ministry of Transport and the World Bank to prepare the schedule, which will be tabled before the World Bank board for approval and rollout.The primary beneficiaries of the programme are the 5.6 million residents of the 59 urban centers, half of whom are women. &ldquo;By achieving this objective, the programme is expected to contribute to the country&rsquo;s over-arching goals of ending extreme poverty and promoting shared prosperity,&rdquo; the statement said.